/*****************************************************************************
    bytecode — incant-side bytecode dispatch (interpretBC).

    interpretBC(body) walks a bytecoded action body and runs each op. (Named
    interpretBC, not interpret, to avoid clashing with the `interpret=`
    sub-attribute each op carries — that attribute is the per-op C++ handler.)

    Dispatch (the 2026-05-30 bcOPs->Operators fold was REVERTED — see setup's
    bcOPs comment): each op carries its own `interpret` sub-attribute,
    inherited from its bcOPs/Operators registry entry. interpretBC reads it
    off the instruction directly — no registry lookup, no fold:
            handler = grup.interpret;
            result  = handler(grup);
        bcOPs remains a SEPARATE registry from Operators (the fold experiment
        failed to parse the emitter source); both just happen to carry
        interpret= on their entries, which is all dispatch needs.

    Stack-form (2026-05-30): operands live on an operand stack hung off the
    body as its `opStack` attribute -- a plain field used as a stack via
    push/pop. interpret() creates it here; producers (bcPushLit/bcPushField)
    push, consumers/op-shims (bcStoreField/runGT/runMultiply) pop, and the
    branch label rides on the instruction's `dst` attribute. Handlers reach the
    stack via opStackOf(instr) -> instr.parent.getAttribute("opStack").

    Successor convention (unchanged):
        result == null  -> fall through to the next sibling instruction.
        result != null  -> branch; reassign grup so the walk continues from the
                           returned target.

    MACHINERY NOTE (corrected 2026-06-04, Brief 5): this is a MEMBER walk
    (`for grup in body; members`), and emitBC DOES attach instructions as
    members — it uses `+=` (opPlusEQ), not `+%`. The old "emitBC uses +%, so
    this loop iterates nothing" claim was stale. The remaining blocker is
    upstream of this walk: bcLIST is born with no groupList, so opPlusEQ's first
    `+=` copies scalar data instead of list-appending and bcLIST never becomes a
    walkable list (see generate's emit-side note + Commands.rtn:162/181). Once
    bcLIST is list-typed at creation (C++/.rtn fix, Tony's seat), this walk sees
    the instructions as members; opStack is hung as an attribute (line 41) so
    the member walk skips it while opStackOf still finds it via getAttribute.
*****************************************************************************/
register(Bytecoding);
define
    interpretBC argument code={
        print `"interpretBC got=" argument.taG " len=" argument.listLengtH:;
        argument +% opStack;
        for grup in argument; members
            handler = grup.interpret;
            if !handler;
                print "interpret: no handler for" grup.taG:;
                return;
            print `"DISP " grup.taG " handler=" handler.taG " method=" handler.isMethod:;
            result = handler(grup);
            if result;  grup = result;
        if opStack.listLengtH;  print "interpret: opStack not empty at end:" opStack.listLengtH:;
        };
    ;
